Note = {27th International Conference on Interactive Collaborative Learning-ICL,
   Tallinn, ESTONIA, SEP 24-27, 2024},
Abstract = {The aim of this research is to provide a theoretical basis for the
   evaluation and application of a variety of digital technologies in music
   therapy, specifying the opportunities that these instruments offer. The
   present study was motivated by the increasing interest the authors have
   observed in the use of technology in music therapy, as well as the
   emergence of research exploring human-AI collaboration in creative music
   activities or live performances, in music composition or production. The
   results of previous research confirm the improvement of
   performance-based music therapy activities, vocal singing or instrument
   singing, when digital technologies are used. However, what is missing at
   the moment is the therapeutic context of these activities and the
   confirmation of their efficacy, by employing them in larger research
   samples (research batch). In this context, the present paper aims to
   bring together a large part of these innovative technological
   applications, in order to make them known and applicable in future music
   therapy research. This paper is interdisciplinary and is intended for
   information technology specialists in the development of software for
   music therapy and music, as well as for specialists in the field of
   music.},
